BLOCK A — Remote Code Execution (RCE)

Definition

> RCE allows an attacker to execute arbitrary code or commands on a target server.




---

Causes

Improper input validation

Unsafe deserialization

Command injection

Vulnerable third-party components

Unsafe file upload



---

Impact

Full server compromise

Data theft

Malware installation

Privilege escalation

Lateral movement



---

Prevention

Validate all user input

Secure coding practices

Least Privilege

Patch Management

Web Application Firewall (WAF)



---

Why is RCE Critical?

Because attackers can execute their own code and potentially take complete control of the server.


---

Remember

> Never trust user input.




---

BLOCK B — Framework & Server Vulnerabilities

Framework

A framework provides reusable components for building applications.

Examples:

Spring Boot

Apache Struts

ASP.NET

Django



---

Why use frameworks?

Faster development

Reusable code

Standardization

Built-in security features



---

Why do framework vulnerabilities affect many companies?

One vulnerable framework can be used by thousands of applications.


---

Patch Lifecycle

Researcher
↓

Find Bug
↓

Vendor Releases Patch
↓

CVE Published
↓

Attackers Build Exploit
↓

Organizations Patch


---

Why Patch?

Because patches remove the root cause.

A firewall or WAF only reduces risk; it doesn't eliminate the vulnerability.


---

Remember

> Outdated software is one of the biggest attack surfaces.




---

BLOCK C — CMS & Plugin Vulnerabilities

CMS

Content Management System

Examples:

WordPress

Drupal

Joomla



---

Why are plugins dangerous?

Every plugin adds:

New code

New permissions

New attack surface



---

Third-Party Risk

Your application inherits vulnerabilities from:

Plugins

Libraries

Dependencies



---

Supply Chain Attack

Instead of attacking your code,

attackers exploit one of your dependencies.


---

Best Practices

Remove unused plugins

Update plugins regularly

Install only trusted plugins

Monitor CVEs

Perform dependency scanning



---

Remember

> Your application is only as secure as its weakest dependency.




